{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655858","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655858"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:06:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:06:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18689"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18689","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18689"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0,0.4,0.52,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11421"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76847"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11421","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11421"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18689"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62352"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10344"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26450"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26459"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76847"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe gray matter of the spinal cord is organised into distinct regions containing different types of neurons. These regions serve specific functions in processing sensory information and generating motor outputs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the arrangement of neurons in the spinal cord gray matter?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Single column of neurons along central canal","Random distribution of neurons throughout gray matter","Sensory neurons located ventrally and motor neurons dorsally","Neurons arranged in distinct laminae with specific functions","Neurons arranged in concentric rings"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that \u003Cstrong\u003Eneurons arranged in distinct laminae with specific functions\u003C/strong\u003E describes the organisation of the spinal cord gray matter. The gray matter contains ten distinct laminae (I-X) arranged in a butterfly-shaped pattern. Laminae I-VI in the dorsal horn primarily process sensory information, laminae VII and X contain interneurons, and laminae VIII-IX in the ventral horn contain motor neurons.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E    \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandom distribution of neurons throughout gray matter\u003C/strong\u003E - The arrangement is highly organised, not random\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENeurons arranged in concentric rings\u003C/strong\u003E - The laminae are arranged in a butterfly pattern, not concentric rings\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESensory neurons located ventrally and motor neurons dorsally\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the opposite of the actual arrangement\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESingle column of neurons along central canal\u003C/strong\u003E - While lamina X surrounds the central canal, neurons are distributed throughout the gray matter\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThis laminar organisation allows for efficient processing of sensory information and generation of motor responses through specific neural circuits.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The gray matter of the spinal cord contains neuronal cell bodies arranged in functional laminae.","The dorsal horn contains sensory neurons and interneurons in laminae I-VI.","The ventral horn contains motor neurons in laminae VIII-IX that innervate skeletal muscles."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62352"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18689"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62352"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T14:09:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T14:10:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11421"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76847"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attribu